Sucrose Polyester
K E Y F A C T S
OVERVIEW
Sucrose polyester (SUE-krose pol-ee-ESS-ter) is an artifi-
cial fat available under the trade names of Olestra or
Olean. The sucrose polyester molecule is quite large and
cannot be absorbed or digested by the human digestive sys-
tem. Since it cannot be digested, it provides no calories to
one’s diet. The compound is used primarily as an additive in
snack treats targeted at people on a diet.
Sucrose polyester is one of many compounds developed
by researchers in an effort to reduce the caloric intake of
people trying to lose weight. Artificial sweeteners designed
for this purpose include saccharin, cyclamates, aspartame,
and acesulfame K. Sucrose polyester is probably the best
known and most successful artificial fat produced so far. It
was developed in the late 1960s by two researchers at Procter
& Gamble’s Miami Valley Laboratories, Robert Volpenhein
and Fred Mattson. Volpenhein and Mattson were looking
for a new kind of fat that could be digested more easily
by premature babies. Instead, they made a very different
